<sn><md>#### I. Tremolite ($\mathrm{Ca_2Mg_5Si_8O_{22}(OH)_2}$)

**General Weathering &amp; Decomposition**
The reaction of tremolite under the influence of ++carbonation and hydration++ produces `talc, magnesium-calcium carbonate compounds, and silica`:

$$\mathrm{Ca_2Mg_5Si_8O_{22}(OH)_2 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow Mg_3Si_4O_{10}(OH)_2 + MgCO_3\cdot CaCO_3 + SiO_2}$$

**Breakdown and Reduction Pathways**
The ++intermediate products++ break down further through the following sequential stages:

$$\begin{aligned} &amp;\text{Reduction of Talc:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{Mg_3Si_4O_{10}(OH)_2 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow MgCO_3 + H_2O + SiO_2} \\ &amp;\text{Magnesium Carbonate Solubilization:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{MgCO_3 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow Mg(HCO_3)_2} \\ &amp;\text{Calcium Carbonate Solubilization:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{CaCO_3 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow Ca(HCO_3)_2} \end{aligned}$$

</md></sn><sn><md>#### II. Actinolite ($\mathrm{Ca_2(Fe,Mg)_5Si_8O_{22}(OH)_2}$)

**Initial Weathering Stages**
`Carbonation and hydration` break down ++actinolite into++ `silicate`, `iron carbonate`, and `magnesium-calcium carbonate` mixtures:

$$\mathrm{Ca_2(Fe,Mg)_5Si_8O_{22}(OH)_2 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow Mg_3Si_4O_{10}(OH)_2 + FeCO_3 + MgCO_3\cdot CaCO_3 + SiO_2}$$

**Subsequent Carbonate and Iron Alteration**

$$\begin{aligned} &amp;\text{Reduction of Talc:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{Mg_3Si_4O_{10}(OH)_2 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow MgCO_3 + H_2O + SiO_2} \\ &amp;\text{Magnesium Carbonate Solubilization:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{MgCO_3 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow Mg(HCO_3)_2} \\ &amp;\text{Calcium Carbonate Solubilization:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{CaCO_3 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow Ca(HCO_3)_2} \\ &amp;\text{Iron Carbonate Oxidation:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{FeCO_3 + O_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow Fe(OH)_3 + CO_2} \end{aligned}$$

**Extreme Weathering Conditions**
Under extreme *climatic pressures*, the ++iron hydroxide++ breaks down completely via high temperatures and oxidation to `form haematite`, which then `hydrates to become limonite`:

$$\mathrm{Fe(OH)_3 \xrightarrow{\text{high temp.}} FeO \xrightarrow{\mathrm{O_2}} Fe_2O_3\ (Haematite)}$$

In the presence of `additional water`, the final alteration yields limonite:

$$\mathrm{Fe_2O_3\ (Haematite) + H_2O \longrightarrow 2Fe_2O_3\cdot 3H_2O\ (limonite)}$$</md></sn>